<gco:CharacterString>This map layer contains a natural-earth image of the conterminous United States. The image is land cover in natural colors combined with shaded relief, which produces a naturalistic rendition of the Earth's surface. The data set is in an Albers Equal-Area Conic projection. The Natural Earth data were produced from existing National Atlas land cover, tree canopy, elevation, and satellite view data.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:abstract>          <gmd:purpose>             <gco:CharacterString>The 100-meter resolution Natural Earth data were developed to portray the terrain and land cover of the United States at 1:1,000,000 scale. They are intended primarily for visual purposes. The original NLCD data or Landsat Thematic Mapper imagery data should be used for conducting scientific analysis, and the original NED data should be used for determining the most accurate elevation values. <gco:CharacterString>The Natural Earth image is a combination of land cover in natural colors and shaded relief. The shaded relief part of the image was created from the National Atlas Elevation data. Relief was rendered with Natural Scene Designer Pro 6.0. The original 100-meter data were down-sampled to 200 meters and received one application of smoothing in NSD Pro 6 prior to relief rendering. Light azimuth = 315 degrees, angle = 45 degrees. Relief was rendered with 200 percent vertical exaggeration in the western US; 300 percent exaggeration in the Appalachians, Adirondacks, Ouachitas, and Ozarks; and 400 percent exaggeration in flat areas of the Midwest and east. Shaded relief was composited in Adobe Photoshop CS6. The Avenza Geographic Imager 4.1 plug-in for Photoshop maintained georeferencing of the shaded relief image. In Photoshop, the relief is composed of four layers that print above land cover: global illumination, high mountain illumination, global shadows, and high mountain shadows. Illumination prints as transparent white, global shadows as transparent black, and high mountain shadows as transparent gray blue. The land cover part of the image was derived from the National Atlas Land Cover, Tree Canopy, and Satellite View data sets. These products were re-colorized and blended in Photoshop to create land cover with natural colors. The Landsat images (satellite view) are most evident in the arid western United States. They also appear as subtle textures in cropland, wetland, and tundra areas. Using "dissolve" blending mode in Photoshop for layers containing NLCD forest data (Land Cover and Tree Canopy) created a slightly pebbled surface to mimic a natural forest canopy. To eliminate small urban areas from the image, urban areas were extracted from the Land Cover data set, aggregated, placed on a layer mask in Photoshop, and a 1-pixel Median filter was applied. Lava received a slight "sandstone" texture created with Photoshop's texturizer filter. Inland water bodies were removed from the land cover with Photoshop's "content aware" fill tool. Manual touch-ups afterwards repaired discordant fill textures.
